#Text=Aleksander Korwin Gosiewski

#Text=Aleksander Korwin Gosiewski ( Lithuanian : Aleksandras Korvinas Gosievskis ) de armis Ślepowron ( b. – d. 1639 ) , was a Polish nobleman , military commander and diplomat , Lithuanian Field-Quartermaster since 1630 , Palatine-Governor of Smolensk from 1625 , Lithuanian Great-Quartermaster since 1615 , Speaker of the Parliament in 1613 , Great-Secretary of the Grand Duchy of Lithuania from 1610 and District-Governor of Wieliż , Puńsk , Kupise , Biel , and Markowa .
#Text=Biography
#Text=Youth
#Text=He came from the noble family Gosiewski of Zambrowski county in the land of Łomża , a family entitled to use the coat of arms Ślepowron .
#Text=He lived in the first half of the 16th century , son of John Gosiewski who was married to Ewa ( née Pac , the Chamberlain of Brest ’ s daughter ) .
#Text=Already in his youth , as Lew Sapieha ’ s courtier , was involved in the affairs of the state .

#Text=In 1600 , as member of Lew Sapieha 's retinue , he played a significant role in the negotiations with Moscovia , editing the planned alliance acts between Poland-Lithuania with the Muscovite state .

#Text=In 1602 , even as District-Governor of Wieliż , attended the drawing of the border between Poland-Lithuania and Moscovia – he became famous repelling a Russian troops attack on his own district .
#Text=Then , during the wars of Sigismund III Vasa against his uncle Charles , the usurper King of Sweden , he served in the Lithuanian army .
#Text=In 1605 , he fought in the Battle of Kircholm .
#Text=In 1606 , as a member of the retinue of Mikołaj Oleśnicki , he escorted Maryna Mniszchówna to Moscow , where he led negotiations for an alliance with Tsar Dmitri .
#Text=Military career
#Text=Aleksander Korwin Gosiewski , Grand Envoy of the Polish – Lithuanian Commonwealth holding the letters of credence to Tsar Dimitry Ivanovich the Pretender
#Text=He was an ardent supporter of Polish military intervention in Moscow during the time of Troubles .
#Text=In July 1609 , he conducted his own expedition to Wielkie Łuki .
#Text=Then he became famous for planting firecrackers to the walls of the fortress during the siege of Smolensk .
#Text=In 1610 at the head of a sizeable branch of the military operation conducted independently in the north of Smolensk , which was to get Bely fortress .
#Text=Subsequently , he reached Moscow , which , after the battle of Klushino was taking by Great-Commander Stanisław Żółkiewski de armis Lubicz .
#Text=In 1610 , he was appointing by Commander Żółkiewski to lead the Polish army commander of the Moscow Kremlin .
#Text=In 1611 the Russians betrayal their old Polish patrons , at the head of a branch off insurrected led to the great fire of Moscow .
#Text=In the year 1612 over the command of the Polish garrison Mikołaj Struś de armis Korczak and returned to Lithuania .
#Text=Residents of the city under the leadership of a merchant Kuzma Minin and Prince Dmitry Pozharsky began to lock the Kremlin .
#Text=The commander of the Polish garrison in the Kremlin , Mikołaj Struś , deprived of relief from the Polish king Sigismund III Vasa , surrendered on 4 November 1612 .

#Text=To commemorate the event tsar Mikhail Romanov instituted a holiday named Day of Moscow ’s Liberation from Polish Invaders in 1613 , in 2004 the public holiday became the Unity Day , which was first celebrated in 2005 .
#Text=In 1612 , the Polish garrison commander at Smolensk fending off all these years numerous attacks of the Russian troops .
#Text=In 1615 , as Lithuanian Field-Quartermaster , he led a small army to block the insurrected Russian army .
#Text=In 1617 and 1618 , Polish Lithuanian troops participated in a failed expedition to Moscow led by Prince Wladyslaw .
#Text=In 1618 , he commanded the garrison during the siege of Smolensk .
#Text=After the arriving of the king 's troops he camped together with the Commander Jan Karol Chodkiewicz ’ troops besieging the city ( Chodkiewicz de armis Kościesza .
#Text=Politics
#Text=Tomb of Aleksander 's son Wincenty Korwin Gosiewski
#Text=He was the Speaker of the Parliament extraordinary held in Warsaw on 3 December to 24 December 1613 .
#Text=During the war with Sweden ( 1621 – 1625 war ) and the ( war 1626 – 1629 ) fought in Livonia winning to the Swedish army at Kroppenhof , Lixna , Slavskoye and Dyneburg .
#Text=It is because of fighting with the Swedes until 1629 , he was appointing Palatine-Governor of Smolensk region , but the nomination was already in 1625 .
#Text=Seeing the threat from Russia , Gosiewski immediately upon taking the governorate of Smolensk began to renovate the walls of the city .
#Text=He personally oversaw the construction of Sigismund Fortress , which strengthened the eastern part of the stronghold .
#Text=Intensively collected supplies of food and ammunition , and developed a business intelligence gathering valuable information about Moscow 's war preparations .
#Text=In the spring of 1632 , he made review the fortifications in Dorogobuzh and other frontier forts .

#Text=During the war with Russia , in the year 1632 and 1634 after a particularly famous defense of Smolensk – for ten months he defended the city against besieging forces led by Mikhail Shein , repelling all assaults , until the advent of the battle led by Prince Władysław .
#Text=He fought at Vitebsk , Alder and Mstislav .
#Text=He participated as a Commissioner in peace negotiations , topped the conclusion on 14 June 1634 , in Treaty of Polanów .
#Text=For his services , he received numerous goods in the province of Smolensk .
#Text=He founded the Jesuits ’ College in Vitebsk and the female Monastery of the Holy Brigit at Brest-Litovsk .
#Text=As Palatine-Governor , he commemorated the death of his longtime client – Jan Kunowski , who in 1640 wrote a series of poems dedicated to his late patron .
#Text=Death
#Text=He died in April 1639 .
#Text=Family
#Text=Aleksander Korwin Gosiewski came from the Ślepowron branch of the family .
#Text=He was married to Ewa Pac .
#Text=They had one daughter , Zuzanna , and two sons ; Wincenty and Krzysztof .
#Text=References and sources
#Text=This new article is a roughly translation after Polish Wikipedia , version 12 March 2013 .
